er` from `lib/dynamodb-client.ts`. My initial implementation checks for the `Bearer` token in the authorization header and, upon decoding, retrieves the user's email to fetch the user from DynamoDB. I'm also including checks for inactive user accounts.\n\n\n**Refactoring to Async**\n\nNow I'm making `getAuthCaller` asynchronous and incorporating `await getAuthCaller(req)` throughout the document routes, improving cleanliness. I'm focusing on `app/api/v1/documents/upload/route.ts` next, but need to tackle `formData` parsing first within Next.js route handlers and will reference `req.formData()` for handling multipart form data uploads.\n\n\n**Defining the Storage Path**\n\nI'm now determining the correct storage path for uploaded files. The parsing of `formData` from `req.formData()` within the Next.js route handler is working; I am now extracting the fields: `client_id`, `project_id`, `title`, `document_type`, `version`, `visibility`, and `description`. I am focused on the path: `./backend/local_s3_storage/${client_id}/documents/${document_id}/${filename}`. I am now working on standardizing the `client_id` for consistency. I am trying to use the same logic in both the frontend and backend. I now need to get the file buffer!\n\n\n**Implementing Local Storage**\n\nI'm now implementing local file storage for the uploaded documents. I'm focusing on creating directories and writing the files using `fs` and `path`. I'm using the DynamoDB key structure to determine the storage path: `./backend/local_s3_storage/${client_id}/documents/${document_id}/${filename}`. The `s3_uri` generation, similar to the Python backend, is up next.\n\n\n"}}
